@WordsofHarmony I am commenting on this " communism in an of itself does not have to be violent."
Actually I dont want to make it sound like socialism or communism must be evil, but communist doctrine does inherently have violent means of collectivisation. Lenist/Stalinist-Soviet communism (so pretty much all kind of communism because it was the guideline for other communists) views itself as an international REVOLUTION and yes those are always violent. Even when you go back to Marxism in "Das Kapital" Marx very much pointed out that the proletariat would rise up in a revolution. Textbook Communism is violent.


This however doesnt mean that Socialism needs to be violent. The proletariat could take over the economy without a revolution in theory, but in that case I wouldnt call it communism because they that is a serious change from Marxs textbook and from Soviet guidelines. Viewing itself as an international revolution that only stops when all of the world is socialist is a big part of marxist thought.
